pr_body:
This PR allows the compilation of basic, single file Rust projects. I'd love to get some feedback on the different options given to `gccrs`, the ones I'm parsing from `rustc` and the implementation's quality overall. There is still a lot of room for improvement but this happily compiles the included basic Rust test. I believe that some necessary improvements are outside the scope of this PR, such as the `-C` option parser. I will definitely work on that and fix it.

Close #3 
Close #4

```yaml

  build_and_test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    
    steps:
    - uses: checkout
    - name: Run rustfmt
      run: cargo fmt -- --check
    # NOTE: no need to build twice
    - name: Run Clippy
      env:
        RUSTFLAGS: "-D warnings" # Trigger an error on warnings
      run: cargo clippy
    - name: Build
      env:
        RUSTFLAGS: "-D warnings" # Trigger an error on warnings
      run: cargo build
    # NOTE: also consider combining cargo build and cargo test and setting `RUSTFLAGS` globally  
    - name: Test
      env:
        RUSTFLAGS: "-D warnings" # Trigger an error on warnings
      run: cargo test
```

I also strongly recommend to include Clippy in the CI pipeline.

pr_title: Allow the compilation of static libraries
pr_body:
Closes #8

This PR also fixes incorrect filename generation for static libraries. I suspect that the bug is also present for shared library building, and I will fix it in a following PR which will also add a test case.

I am looking for feedback regarding the callback system and implementation. The provided callback currently creates an empty archive. Thus, we must also decide of a set naming scheme for temporary object files and where to put them. Maybe this is something that cargo already asks rustc to do and we could look into it

pr_body:
Closes #14 

This PR makes `InvalidArg` errors clearer, which in turn will help development:

```sh
> cargo gccrs build
thread 'main' panicked at 'cannot translate rustc arguments into gccrs ones: InvalidArg("Unrecognized option: \'cfg\'")', src/main.rs:29:14
note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace
thread 'main' panicked at 'cannot translate rustc arguments into gccrs ones: InvalidArg("Unrecognized option: \'cap-lints\'")', src/main.rs:29:14
note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace
```

pr_body: This PR adds a basic test harness with various wrappers around the operations tests need to use. For now, this only checks that the included basic projects compile using `rustc` and `gccrs`.

pr_title: Allow extra arguments from environment variables
pr_body:
Closes #20 

This PR allows the user to specify extra arguments to give to `gccrs` or `ar` via the `GCCRS_EXTRA_ARGS` and `AR_EXTRA_ARGS` environment variables.

Once the project is usable and documentation exists, there should be a section dedicated to the environmental variables that it uses.

Note that the aim is not to replace the use of `RUSTFLAGS`: This is simply in case the user would want to give extra arguments to `gccrs` specifically.

pr_title: Check correct filename between rustc and gccrs
pr_body:
This PR adds functional testing for checking that the binaries produced by `rustc` and `gccrs` both have the same filename.

One thing that I'm not too happy with is that we cannot benefit from having multiple tests. Since tests run in parallel, and that AFAIK there is no way to specify `--test-threads=1` in a configuration file, we are stuck with having to check a lot of conditions for each test folder, all at once, or else we'd run in parallelism issues. 

I guess we could at least split the main functional test function (`check_compilation`) but it would mean changing the way we compile projects, as this implementation currently `cd`s into the project directory before building it.

pr_body:
This PR cleans up the `GccrsArgs` type by splitting it in multiple modules. As pointed out by @philberty and @flip1995, the type should be doing much less than what is currently implemented.

Closes #23
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 671344412, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
        Ok(self.options.parse(&args[2..])?)
```

And see if Clippy complains about this and tells you to remove the `Ok(_?)` wrap.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 16, 15, 30, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671354042, 'comment_body': 'To rustify this, you would want to implement 
```rs
impl TryFrom<RustcOptions> for Vec<GccrsArgs> { ... }
```

But this isn't possible, since you can't implement an external trait for an external type `Vec`.

What you normally do in this case is to make a wrapper type that wraps the `Vec<_>` and implements `Deref`.

For this, a possible name for the wrapper type would be `GccrsArgss` (2 `s`). And this is the point where it doesn't make sense to me why `GccrsArgs` is called `GccrsArgs`, when you need multiple instances to get all `Args` for `Gccrs`. The name "`GccrsArgs`" already implies, that you have every arg, but for some reason there is still the need for a `GccrsArgs"s"`.

From a user perspective I would expect something like this:

```rs
// Parse the arguments cargo provides for rustc and try to convert them to arguments that can be passed to gccrs
let args: GccrsArgs = RustcOptions::new().parse(rustc_args)?.try_into()?;
// build the gccrs command with the arguments converted from the rustc arguments
let gccrs = Command::new("gccrs").args(args.into());
// Run gccrs
```

Also why is `RustcOptions` called `Options` and `GccrsArgs` called `Args`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 16, 15, 43, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 671354575, 'comment_body': 'I still think, that `GccrsArgs` should handle nothing but the parsing/conversion of arguments.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 16, 15, 44, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672907768, 'comment_body': 'No complaints from clippy!
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 8, 16, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672945395, 'comment_body': 'Fixed in 8b442e6', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 9, 8, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672947971, 'comment_body': 'Fixed in 4aa2cab and 7eb1f3b', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 9, 11, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672948654, 'comment_body': 'Sorry about the clock skew
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 9, 12, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 673059814, 'comment_body': 'I would implement this on `RustcOptions` and not on `&[String]` directly.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 12, 3, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 673075675, 'comment_body': 'IIUC most of the `Options` are common to all `gccrs` invocations. So

```bash
rustc --crate-type=dyn --crate-type=bin src/<file>.rs --other-flag-1 --other-flag-2
```

becomes

```bash
gccrs src/<file>.rs --converted-other-flag-1 --converted-other-flag-2  # bin
gccrs -shared src/<file>.rs -o libfile.so --converted-other-flag-1 --converted-other-flag-2  # shared lib
```

where `--converted-other-flag-1 --converted-other-flag-2` are common to all invocations. So why not only store them once?

```rust
pub struct OptionsCollection {
    common_args: Vec<Arg>,
    crate_types: Vec<CrateType>,
    ... // Other fields that require multiple gccrs invocations, if any
}
```

I think that would make things way cleaner and would avoid saving the common options and input+output file name `N` times. 

Maybe even:

```rust
pub struct Args {
    input_files: Vec<String/PathBuf>,
    output_file: String/PathBuf,
    common_args: Vec<Arg>,
    crate_types: Vec<CrateType>,
    ... // Other fields that require multiple gccrs invocations, if any
}
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 12, 28, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 673084862, 'comment_body': 'And only once you generate the `gccrs` cmmands, you will build the whole `Vec<Vec<String>>` argument matrix.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 12, 40, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674641954, 'comment_body': 'Fixed in 2b39f21', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 22, 9, 32, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674651927, 'comment_body': "As of right now, there aren't many shared options since the translator does not do much. I think your design makes a lot of sense for when we will handle all Rustc arguments (for example, after #46 is done). The only shared arguments for now are `-fPIE` and `-pie` on the `main` branch. I'm not against it but it's a bit hard to wrap my head around it with the current implementation. How do you feel about opening an issue and doing this in a later PR? If you think it's really important I'll try and do it now :)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 22, 9, 47, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CohenArthur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674720080, 'comment_body': "IMO simply the fact that you currently clone the input and output names N times would already warrant this design. And in the future there probably will be more shared arguments. So the current design, where you have to clone all of those arguments N times isn't scalable. 

Since this PR already improves the situation a bit, I'm good with merging this for now and to keep the technical debt.  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 22, 11, 41, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
Needs #47 to be merged

Closes #16
Closes #17 

This PR adds the handling of those options to the rustc option parser generator. This will no longer be an issue once #46 is done, but is necessary for now in order to compile certain crates.

I added the corresponding compiler issues links (Rust-GCC/gccrs#575 and Rust-GCC/gccrs#574) in the commit's message for future reference

pr_title: Split up project in library and binary
pr_body:
Closes #19 
Closes #22 
In reference to [this comment](https://github.com/Rust-GCC/cargo-gccrs/pull/15#pullrequestreview-688108719)

@flip1995 I am unsure about the implementation as I usually just panic when handling errors in the main haha. I believe this to be cleaner, as it displays useful information and exits using `std::process::exit()` rather than panicking.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 665133144, 'comment_body': "Why do you need a wrapper for this? Do you plan to do more things with this wrapper in the future? If not, I'd just implement the `spawn()` function here directly.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 7, 7, 56, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 665140117, 'comment_body': "I'd rather name this `gccrs-driver` to stick to the rustc naming.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 7, 8, 5, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 665144475, 'comment_body': 'Wait, does this handle both the `driver` and the `cargo` part? So if you call `cargo gccrs build`, this binary will execute itself with the same arguments?

When is this called with `gccrs` vs `rustc`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 7, 8, 11, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'flip1995', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 665192048, 'comment_body': "That's what I had done originally but thought it'd be cleaner from the binary side of things. pr_title: Merge both module classes in one
pr_body:
This PR merges both kinds of Modules (formerly `ModuleBodied` and `ModuleNoBody`) as one class with an enum. This is the [behavior used by rustc](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/2939249f294dd54a9ce78a8ee1f2922a44e7fb7c/compiler/rustc_ast/src/ast.rs#L2274), where both variants are kept in an enum with one holding a vector of items.

This change is important for multiple file parsing: An external mod (`mod foo; // defined in foo.rs or foo/mod.rs`) will see its items expanded during expansion, which occurs after parsing. This means that the previous directive will be "replaced" by `mod foo { <items> }` at the AST level. In order to achieve this, we need to be able to modify a previously parsed instance of an AST element.

In rustc, this is done [here](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/2939249f294dd54a9ce78a8ee1f2922a44e7fb7c/compiler/rustc_expand/src/expand.rs#L1427), where `mod_kind` was previously `ModKind::Unloaded` and becomes `ModKind::Loaded(parsed_items, ...)`.

pr_body:
In order to support multiple file parsing, we will need to be able to parse items from a file without specifically parsing an entire crate. This PR splits up the `parse_crate()` function in two and exposes the `parse_items()` function.

The function was previously hidden and didn't have the exact same behavior as the main loop of `parse_crate()`.

This will be especially useful when trying to expand 
```rust
mod <file>;
```
to
```rust
mod <file> {
    <items>
}
```
in the AST as we will need to parse the items present in the file.

pr_title: Turn Session Manager into basic singleton
pr_body:
This PR changes the behavior of the compiler's session manager: Instead of keeping a single static instance in `rust-lang.cc`, the class now exposes a static instance via a `get_instance()` method. This is important for external module parsing as a new lexer and parser need to be instantiated during macro expansion, and a lexer must rely on a linemap, of which a single instance exists and is contained in the `Session` instance.

I ran into a few issues trying to make this a bit smarter (for example, by calling `init()` on the first `get_instance()` invocation) because I ran into a race condition. I haven't looked into it, but it seems that the calls to the various language hooks are sometimes multithreaded.

pr_body:
This PR is a first attempt at resolving the filename corresponding to an external module correctly. Some of the cases are not handled yet and a lot of FIXMEs are still here, as I am looking for feedback on certain things:

* Am I correct in assuming that we have to go through directories the C way because we are using C++11 and the `filesystem` header is not available until C++17? Is there some gcc abstraction for this that I'm overlooking?
* How important is the existence of a separate SEPARATOR macro for Windows? From what I'm understanding, the OS also understands normal slashes `/` on top of the backward slashes it usually uses `\`. I don't know what happens when they are mixed and matched or how the file system handles it.
* For review simplicity, outer attributes could be accessed in a later PR. I believe they can already be accessed and looked at but haven't looked into it. I'm also unsure if this would be the right place to implement that outer_attr lookup
